explanation.prod-public-otel-alb-1851299546.us-east-: Contains 'otel' / OpenTelemetry on an ELB host — external telemetry/metrics endpoint; block.
explanation.routing.bgp.technology: Unusually high-volume queries from RMI_NAS to a nonstandard TLD/name. Could be misconfiguration, monitoring tool, or malicious; watch and map to the NAS process before action.
explanation.tracker.birkenwald.de: Explicit 'tracker' hostname seen from the NAS. Torrent trackers can be legitimate for a NAS torrent client — place on WATCH for user decision.
explanation.tracker.tiny-vps.com: Explicit 'tracker' hostname. Do not blindly block trackers; WATCH so the user can confirm legitimacy (torrent vs malicious).
explanation.tracker.torrent.eu.org: Torrent-style tracker observed — WATCH since trackers may be required by legitimate torrent clients on the NAS.
explanation.tracker.opentrackr.org: Public tracker host. WATCH to let user confirm whether NAS is running torrent clients or this is unwanted activity.
explanation.ipv4.tracker.harry.lu: Contains 'tracker' prefix — WATCH (likely tracker/torrent related; verify with owner).
explanation.tracker.moeking.me: Tracker-style host ('.me' TLD) — WATCH rather than immediate block so user can confirm intent.
explanation.tracker.cyberia.is: Tracker host observed from NAS — place on WATCH to determine whether torrenting is expected.
explanation.open.stealth.si: Uncommon host queried by the NAS at low volume — WATCH while investigating which service/process on NAS contacts it.
explanation.explodie.org: Unfamiliar host contacted by the NAS; low volume but unusual — WATCH and map to NAS services.
explanation.dns.msftncsi.com: Microsoft network connectivity check — part of essential OS behavior and explicitly exempted from blocking; ALLOW.
explanation.api.insight.synology.com: Synology 'insight' endpoint queried heavily by the NAS. synology.com is in TRUSTED_DOMAINS so MUST be ALLOWED; monitor NAS configuration and telemetry settings on the device.
explanation.checkip.synology.com: Synology external-IP check used by the NAS — part of expected Synology behavior; ALLOW.
explanation.telemetry.qdrant.io: qdrant.io is in TRUSTED_DOMAINS. Per rules, any matching domain must be ALLOWED even if it contains 'telemetry'.
explanation.otel.gitkraken.com: gitkraken.com is in TRUSTED_DOMAINS. Although it contains 'otel', TRUSTED_DOMAINS rules require ALLOW.
explanation.notify.dropboxapi.com: dropboxapi.com is trusted. These calls likely relate to NAS integrations/backups; ALLOW to avoid breaking functionality.
explanation.api.dropboxapi.com: Dropbox API activity from the NAS — TRUSTED_DOMAINS mandates ALLOW; verify integrations if concerned.
explanation.plex.tv: Plex metadata/control calls from the NAS. plex.tv is trusted and ALLOW prevents breaking Plex functionality.
explanation.scrobbles.plex.tv: Plex scrobbling is optional telemetry-like behavior but plex.tv is trusted; ALLOW per rules (user can disable scrobbling in Plex if desired).
explanation.spaceship.dev: Listed as TRUSTED_DOMAINS and seen on the NAS. ALLOW but verify if this developer domain is expected by installed NAS services.
explanation.github.com: Active developer/service usage on the network; trusted and commonly used — ALLOW.
explanation.raw.githubusercontent.com: Developer CDN in active use (downloads) — ALLOW for functionality.
explanation.api.github.com: Developer API usage from user machines — ALLOW.
explanation.log.tailscale.io: tailscale.io is trusted and indicates Tailscale logging/coordination; ALLOW if Tailscale is intentionally used for remote access.
explanation.google.com: Core Google domain used by clients; benign and allowing avoids breaking user services.
explanation.connectivitycheck.gstatic.com: Google connectivity check / infra — do not block (Google infra allowed).
explanation.pool.ntp.org: NTP pool requests from router/clients — legitimate infrastructure; ALLOW.
explanation.api.openai.com: Seen from user device(s) representing user-driven service usage; allow unless policy requires otherwise.
explanation.www.apple.com: Apple infrastructure (NEVER BLOCK *.apple.com) — ALLOW to avoid breaking OS/app functionality.
